{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_groot_ver01/data/sn87062224/0051415689A/1958021401/0268.xml":{"full_text":"MILFORD CHRONICLE\nESTABLISHED OCTOBER 4, 1*78\nTHEO. TOWNSEND\nEditor and Proprietor from 1878 to 1810\nMILFORD CHRONICLE PUBLISHING COMPANY\n10 TO 10 SOOTH WEST FRONT STREET\nMILFORD, DP.LAWARE\nPUBLISHERS\n-President\n_Vice-President\n-Secretary-Treasurer\nQ. Marshall Townsend.\nVirginia S. Townsend\nTheodore Townsend._\nQ. Marshall Towncend\nRobert H. Yerkea...\n_Editor\nManaging Editor\nExclusive National Advertising Representative\nGreater Weeklies\nNew York Chicago Detroit Philadelphia\nSubscription Terms\nBt Mall\u2014In Delaware, $\u00ee SO a Tear\nOutside of Delaware. 93.00 ft Year\nSingle Copies.\n-Six Cents\nPHONE\u2014MILFORD 4521\nAddress all communications to the Milford Chronlcls\nPublishing Company, Milford, Delaware\nEntered u second-claxs matter March 3, 1179 at the\npost office at Milford, Del., under Act of March 3, 1ST\u00bb\n\nDELA WARES LEADING WEEKLY NEWSPAPER\nThe Milford Chronicle is Delaware's largest weekly\nnewspaper\u2014both in size of paper, number of pages printed,\nvolume of news carried, and lineage of advertising pre\nsented each lasue. All advertising is sold on a basis of\na guaranteed circulation of over 7,000 copies each issue.\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is entitled exclusively to the\nuse for republication of all the k>\u00e7al news printed In\nthis newspaper, as well as all AP news dispatches.\nFRIDAY, FEBRUARY 14, 1958\nOUTER SPACE TRAVEL\nRecent surveys have shown that the pop\nulation of the world is increasing by some\n43,000,000 citizens a year. The boom in world\npopulation began after World War II and\nBecause there are no longer many large\nurftler-developed countries, where people are\nnever adequately fed, clothed or sheltered. In\nfact, it is reported that more than half the\nUnless scientific and technological im\nprovements can keep pace, and then some,\nwith the growing population, millions and\nmillions of babies and young people will con\ntinue to go hungry, and the figure might even\nincrease. This aggravates an already press\ning population problem, especially in coun\ntries like China and India.\nAll of which brings us around to the ques\ntion of outer space. There are some who won\nder why scientists and defense officials are\nmaking plans to travel to outer space. In\ntime it may be that we will need the unde\nveloped lands or productive surface areas of\nsome of the planets that surround us.\nis continuing steadily.\nareas of productive land open for migration,\nand because the world has shrunk and popu\nlation increased daily, a problem is to be\nfaced, eventually, concerning the feeding,\nclothing and housing of our steadily increas\ning population.\nBirth rates, of course, are the highest in\npeople on earth today are hungry.\none can answer question\nfinality until outer space is explored and that\nis the reason why the scientists of the world,\nand some of the world's humanitarians, are\ngenuinely interested in outer space travel for\nreasons connected with our sharply-inoreas\ning population.\nPresident Eisenhower clings to his belief\nthat the current recession is only a, \"breath\ner\" for business, a view which is not shared\nby all of our economists. They may be an up\nturn a few months hence, but it would be\nunwise to simply wait for that to happen.\nSecretary of Labor Mitchell has said that*\nWAR AGAINST RECESSION\nthere will be four and a half million unem\nployed this month. This is too deep an eco\nnomic breath for America to afford at this\nprecise moment in history. If the recession\nbecomes more severe the uncommitted world,\nimpelled by fear, may well fling itself into\nthe lap of Russia.\nIt is unsafe to bank on defense spending\nalone as a means of pulling the business spir\nal back upwards. For then, if any disarma\nment agreements were reached, our economy\ncould be sucked back into another recession.\nThat economy is delicately organized and is\ntoo big and complicated to be allowed to run\non its own momentum;\nBy easing its monetary policies, the gov\nernment has already taken some of the steps\nthat can be taken to speed economic recovery.\nFurther steps could be taken without raising\nthe bugaboo of government intervention.\nRecession need not find us helpless. Re\ncession is a challenge to reason and inge\nnuity. The nation must be ready now so as\nto be able to prevent depression. For depres\nsion is the precise development that Moscow\nhas hoped for and waited for since the end\nof World War II. Imaginative action to curb\nand shorten the recession is the best way to\nmake sure that those hopes will be disap\npointed.\nWHAT HAPPENED TO SCHOOLROOM\nCRISIS? v\nThe proposal that the federal government\nunderwrite scientific education is running\ninto strong opposition\u2014and some of it tomes\nfrom top educators. They see federal aid as\nan open sesame to ultimate federal control\nof education. They want to get the needed\nmoney from industry, foundations and indi\nviduals.\nThe situation caused the Wall Street\nJournal to make an apt observation. \"This\nyear we are told that unless Washington\nspends $1 billion more on science education\nwe will never catch up to the Russian Sput\nniks and education is doomed.\nLast year we were told that unless the\nFederal Government came across* with bil\nlions of dollars to build schoolrooms across\nthe country education was doomed. But hard\nly anybody mentions that these days.\nis it fair to ask the Federal aiders what\nhappened to the schoolroom crisis?\nThose who want the federal government\nto become a dictator of education will use\nany excuse to get their foot in the door. That\nis happening now. It amounts to arguing\nthat we must ape the Russians in order to\nkeep pace with the Russians. If that is true,\nfree and representative government is dead.\nOne of the great paradoxes of this age is\nthat we could destroy ourselves from within\neven as we gird mightily to guard against\nattack from without.\n\n\nTHE FEBRUARY SKY\nThis is a good month to study the sky and\nthe stars because the clarity of winter nights,\neven though it is cold, gives the stars a bril\nliance likening them to diamonds. If you\ncan stand the weather, then, February is one\nof the best months to practice your amateur\nastronomy.\nThe Indians called February the month\nof the Hunger Moon because it was tne\nmonth in which they had most trouble pro\nviding food for their families.. Fish were\nburied under thick ice, the ground was froz\nen hard, digging was difficult, dried berries\nand greens were now almost non-existent. In\naddition, bears were in hibernation and it\nwas difficult to find enough game.\nSince you do not have to obtain your food\nlike the Indians, you might very well use\nFebruary as a month to learn about the sky\nand the stars. Begin by finding the familiar\nBig Dipper. The Big Dipper also goes by\nother names, such as Great Bear, Ursa Ma\njor, Plough, and Charles' Wain. Notice the\ntwo outer stars of the bowl, which are known\nas the Pointers. They always point to the\nNorth Star, which is also known as Polaris.\nTonight, if you search the sky, you will\nfind this to be true. You will also notice that\nthe handle of the Dipper is composed of three\nstars 'and that very near the central star is\nanother star, which is much smaller. Many\npeople do not see this star, and it must be\nobserved on a clear night, with the naked\neye.\nThe name of this little star is Alcor and\nthe n.iddle-handle star is Mizar. These two\nstars were known to the Arabs as the Horse\nand Rider. They form a double gvar, which\nwas the first double star to be discovered\n(1850). The open part of the Dipper's bowl\npoints into the open part of the bowl of the\nLittle Dipper constellation. The North Star,\nyou can observe, is in the end of the handle\nof the Little Dipper.\nAs you are observing the sky, and famil\niarizing yourself with the familiar Big Dip\nper, or Littl\u00e7 Dipper, or North Star, remem\nber that if these stars had ceased to exist\neighty or ninety years ago, you woi^ld still\nbe seeing them, since their light beams would\nbe traveling to the earth. Knowing that light\ntravels at terrific speed, one can well imag\nine what he is seeing, and the great distance\nhe is investigating in studying th\u00df sky,\nFEBRUARY\nThe name \"February\" comes from the\nLatin verb, \"Februare\", which means to pur\nify. The Romans formerly held a festival at\nwhich a goat .was sacrificed, after which the\npriests struck the hands of women with a\nstrip of the skin of a goat, which was sup\nposed to insure fertility and a safe delivery,\nIn United States history February is no\ntable as a month of birthday anniversaries,\nThe foremost birthday anniversary of the\nmonth is that of George Washington, the\nfounder of the country, whose reputation has\ngrown by leaps and bounds in recent years.\nIt is also the month in which the birthday\nanniversary of Abraham Lincoln falls. Wash\nington's birthday comes on February 22nd\nand Lincoln's on February 12th.\nOther birthdays of interest include those\nof Charles Dickens, who was born February\n7th, 1812, at Landport, England. The anni\nversary of the chartering of the Boy Scouts\nof America falls on February 8th. The char\ntering took place on February 8th, 1910.\nThe birthday anniversary of William\nHenry Harrison, ninth president of the Uni\nted States, comes on February 9th. Harrison\nwas born in Charles County, Virginia, on\nFebruary 9th, 1773.\nAn often-forgotten anniversary is that of\nthe Spanish peace treaty, the signing of\nwhich, by the president, occurred on Febru\nary 10th, 1899. By that treaty Spain ceded\nto the United States the Philippine Islands\nand the island of Guam in the Pacific, and\nthe island of Puerto. Rico, in the Atlantic. In\nconsideration of a payment of $20,000,000,\nSpain also agreed to withdraw from Cuba.\nSt. Valentine's Day falls on February\n14th. Jefferson Davis was inaugurated 'as\nPresident of the Confederacy on February\n18th, 1861. The Washington Monument was\ndedicated on February 21st, 1885.\nHenry Wadsw.orth Longfellow, one of the\nmost popular American poets of the nine\nteenth century, was born February 27th,\n1807, in Portland, Maine.\nON BUSINESS LUNCHES\nUncle Sam has declared that the expense\naccount businessman, who for many years\nnow has been enjoying eating out, and charg\ning the cost to business expense, will be lim\nited to some degree this year. The limitation\nconsists of an we rule that the businessman\ncannot buy himself lunch, even while enter\ntaining a guest, while in his home town.\nAs soon as this announcement was made,\nall sorts of questions were raised about one's\nhome town. Could a businessman, for ex\nample, drive five or ten miles to the nearest\nmunicipality, perhaps in the same greater\nmetropolitan area, and charge it all to the\nexpense account in that community.\nUncle Sam says \"No.\" Moreover, Uncle\nSam says that businessmen on trips must be\non overnight trips or their expense accounts\nmight be rejected. All in all, taken with the\nannouncement by Uncle Sam that expense\naccounts would have to be justified in more\ndetail next year (covering this year's ex\npenditures) it seems that the expense ac\ncount money is taking it on the chin.\nEver since the high tax rates have been in\neffect, for some fifteen years now, the United\nStates economy has drifted toward an econ\nomy of the expense account executive. Apart\nments, automobiles, and all sorts of things\nwere bought on expense accounts. This was\na way of circumventing income taxes and\nmuch of the restaurant and night club and\nentertainment money in the larger cities of\nthis country can be traced to the expense\naccount. It is an artificial situation, which\ninflates prices and makes things pretty ter\nrible for the private citizen without an ex\npense account, who is trying to compete with\nthe expense-account gentry. While we hate\nto admit agreeing with the tax man, there is\nreason for requiring justification for certain\nexpense outlays\u2014in fairness to everyone con\ncerned.\nABOVE THE CLOUDS\nA\nSUMM/r\ns\u00c7 MEET \\nq\nri\n!S\u00ef\n\u25a0Ss\n\n\nSS\nA\nPROOF OF 5 WC\u00a3ff/ rv\ngy SOVIET\n\n'\u20222S\n'm\n\nTj\njM\n\n\n\u25a0S'\n\n\u25a0SS\nS:\nS'\nm\n1\nT\nf I\n<s\nr?\n-v\n\u2022r\nv?\nBABSON DISCUSSES BEAL ESTATE AND WEATHEB\nBabson Park, Fla., Feb. 13 A few\nweeks ago I was asked by a friend\nto go twenty miles from here and\nlook at a piece of Florida property,\nThe weather here had been\nwretched, cold and rain with con\nstant fog. Very few people were on\nthe streets or in the stores. The\nrestaurant where I expected to get\nluncheon was closed, with a sign\nthat it would be open \"when the\nsun comes out\". Even the real\nestate offices that I visited were\nclosed. When I found one of the\nmen at his home, he said that\nit was impossible to sell real estate\n.\"during weather like this.\"\nWeather And Land Sales\nApparently most people lack vi\nsion. When it is sunny, they think\nit will always be sunny; but when\nit has rained for a week, they\nthink it will always rain. They\nlack vision as to temperature. The\nreal estate men claim that their\nbusiness is \"Reasonable\"; that most\nreal state buyers lack reason and\nforesight. This is why most sellers\nof real estate are obliged to work\non a commission basis. The weather\nprimarily explains why the real\nestate business is so cyclical.\nEvery business is more or less\ncyclical, constantly revolving like\na wheel. Most people buy at the top\nand sell at the bottom; a few buy at\nthe bottom and sell at the top.\nThose, however, who get aboard the\nwheel at any point and s'tay with\nit, dealing with honest brokers,\nas usually come out satisfactorily.\nThis applies to land and buildings\nGirl Scout News\nr'\nI 1\nr\nk\nT\nOi\n\ni ti\nw\nMay I extend my sincere thanks\nto all who took over my duties\nduring the past few weeks. Many\ngood deeds were done on my be\nhalf by my sister Scouts and their\ninterest and concern were indeed a\ncomfort.\nThe Girl Scout Cookie Sale will\nend on February 15. Mrs. Frank\nAppel, neighborhood cookie chair\nman, reports that she appreciates\nthe eagerness and spirit which the\nBrownies and Girl Scouts have\nshown during the Cookie Sale. She\nis very well pleased with the pro\ngress of the sale and wishes to\nstate that there are still some more\ncookie mints and one case of as\nsorted sandwich cookies, if any\none is interested in acquiring addi\ntional cookies. The true Girl Scout\nspirit was shown on the opening\nday of the sale. Even though the\nday was snowy and cold Mrs. Ap\npel had repated calls for cookies\nthat the girls were determined to\nsell. A complete report will be\ngiven by Mrs. Appel at a future\ndate.\nA Girl Scouts honor is to be\ntrusted. This is one of her laws.\nHonor is defined as respectful\nregard, esteem, reputation, self-re\nspect. When a Brownie or a Girl\nScout is placed on her honor, there\nshould never be any question as to\nthe outcome of her deed. Yet it has\nbeen reported, with regret, that dur\ning the beginning of the Cookie Sale,\nwhen all Brownies and Girl Scouts\nhad been placed on their honor not\nto sell cookies until the morning\nof Saturday. Feb. 1st some cookies\nhad been sold before this date,\nHonor is far more important to a\nGirl Scout than the selling of\ncookies. Involved also is the goal\nof selling the most boxes and gain\ning an earned reward. Leaders are\nrequested to discuss the subject of\nhonor with their girls again and\nwhen they tally tue number of\nboxes sold by each girl, remember\nthe winner is the girl who waited\nuntil Saturday morning to start\nthe competition, for in Scouting\nthere is no such word as foul plav.\nand Girl Scout of Milford? It would\nbe interesting to find out. and so\nall leaders are being asked to find\nthe girl ;n their troop who can best\nnnalifv as an outstanding scout,\nThis is not a popularity contest\nWhe. the outsanding Brownie\nas well as to sto\u00e7ks and bonds. It\nmeans that the shrewd buyer buys\nduring periods of bad'weather and\nbad news. This, pioreover, applies\nto all sections of the country as\nsome section is always suffering\nfrom long rains, or long droughts,\nor long cold spells, or long hot\nspells. These, however, are the\nperiods when it is best to buy real\nestate.\nSwampy Land Should Become\nMore Valuable\nUp to the present time, pasture\nland or raw land that is swampy\nhas sold at a very low price,\u2014prob\nably only one-quarter of what well\nlocated pasture land would bring.\nWet land cannot successfully grow\norchards of fruit trees. Cattle like\nponds in their pasture; but they\nmust have dry land to feed upon.\nRice and cranberries are about\nthe only commercial crops which\ncan use wet land.\nStatistics show, however, that the\nwater table of most states is grad\nually but seriously falling. Most\nstates now have commissions which\nare engaged in studying the water\ntable. This decline in the supply of\nwater is due to various causes; one\nowner will drain his property and\nforget that he is also draining his\nneighbors' property which needs\nmore water Every state is endeav\noring to get some industries, and\nyet most industries are large con\nsumers of water. This means that\nwater will become of great value\nsome day. Cheap swamp land\nshould, therefore, constantly become\nan event to cause any unfriendly\nfeelings. But it is a challenge of\nthe troops to introduce to Milford\nthe girl who is a typical scout, It;\nshould be decided between the\ngirls themselves with the aid of\ntheir leaders. It should take several\nweeks of discussion before the\nor\nchoice is made. Each troop will then\nsubmit the name of their girl to a\nboard of judges and the name of\nthe two girls chosen will be an\nnounced during Girl Scout Week.\nThere is no prize being offered to\nthese girls, just a satisfaction of\ngreat pride and honor. Girls should\nbe judged on the importance of\ntheir uniform to them. The way\nthey wear it and the pride and\ncare they take of it. Their atten\ndance in scouting, not only at their\nown meetings, but to outside func\ntions they have been asked to\nparticipate in. Their attitude to\nwards scouting and the progress\nthey have made. Also the manner\nin which they display scouting\nthroughout their daily lives, in\nthought, word, and deed. These\ncertainly are not all the qualities of\nan outstanding scout, that is why\nwe suggest a period of discussion\nbefore decision.\nThe twelve Girl Scout Troops in\nMilford have been divided among\nthree troop consultants, Mrs. Park\nHitch, Mrs. Finley Jones and\nMrs. Roy LaFontaine. These con\nsultants w'ork together with the\nneighborhood chairman, Mrs. Chas.\nLundstedt. Mrs. Hitch is consul\ntant for four Brow lie troops under\nthe leadership of Mrs. Joe Moors,\nMrs. Claude Lynch and Mrs. Door\nthy Rathmell. Mrs. LaFontaine is\nconsultant for Brownie Troops un\nder the leadrship, of Mrs. Clyde\nWilkins, and Mrs. Elwood Mont\nand the new intermediate\ner\nMiss Virginia Gray. It is the job of\nthe consultant to help the leader\nto become acquainted, establish a\nfriendly relationship with her, and\ndevelop mutual understanding and\nacceptance. To be available when\nthe leader asks for help. When a\nproblem can not be solved by a\nconsultant, the consultant will take\nit to the neighborhood chairman for\ndiscussion. If there is a need, the\nneighborhood chairman can get\nadvice direcr f rom Council. No\nleader need ever feel that she is i\nwithout help or advice. Your con\nsultant hopes to become one of\njyour closest associates in scouting,\n\"You can depend upon her for\nServW\". This will be the Theme\nused bv all Girl Scouts during their\nweek March 9 through March 15\nPlans are being completed for a\nvery active week. All troops are\npreparing a 5-8 minute program\ngomery\ntroop under Miss Janet Lofland.\nMrs. Jones is consultant for the\nIntermediate Troops under\nleadership of Mrs. Clement Nevins,\nMrs. Parker Hitch, Mrs. Charles\nLundstedt and Mrs Frank Lynch,\nalso for the Senior Scouts under\nthe\nmore valuable and should be a good\npurchase today for those who have\n\n1 e pa en e J,\nSurplus Water From Canada\nI have already spoken in this\ncolumn of the \"John Powers, Jr.\nPlan\" to bring surplus water from\nWestern Canada down through\nNorth Dakota into the dry sections\nnear our Rocky Mountains. Tre\nmendous reserves of fresh water\nare now running northward into\nthe Arctic Ocean. Mr. Powers\nsows that, with the permission of\nCanada, these waters could be\nturned southerly to irrigate, at\nslight cost, the \"Great American\nDesert\". It would cost no more\nthan it costs to build modern turn\npikes for automobiles. As this may\ncome about sooner than most peo\nple realize, I advise people not to\nsacrifice such waste land they\nmight now own in Utah, New Mexi\npo and Arizona.\nComing back to the theme of\nthis week's column, let me urge\nreal estate salesmen to educate\ntheir prospects as to the most\nsuitable seasons to buy real estate.\nInstead of going on vacations dur\ning the \"off season\", they should\nadvertise that the \"off seasons\" are\nthe best times to get bargains. They\nwould also stabilize what is now\na hazardous occupation, dependent\non buisness conditions, on seasons\nof the year, and upon rain, snow,\nfog, drought, insects, gales, and\nalmost every other uncertainty.\nfor Parents Night. The Girl Scouts\nwill entertain on March 12 at 7:30\nand the Bsownies on March 14 at\n7:00 p. m. Both Mon and Dad are\nasked to attend this event, for it\nis felt that Dad does not have\nmuch opoprtunity to observe his\ndaughters scouting activities. Sun\nday, March 9, it is hoped that all\ngirls plan to attend church to\ngether, either at the Avenue Church\nat St. John's Church.\nor\nOBITUARY\ni n addition to his wife, Mr. Ad\nams leaves two sons, Stanley and\nLester Adams, both of Plyladel\nphia; two daughters, Mrs. John\nSchoot, Chester and Mrs. Walter\nJ. Hanson. Harrington; four sis\nters, Mrs. Katie Drummond, Santa\nRosa, Calif., Mrs. tVilliam Crdll,\nHickman, Mrs. August Croll, Fed\neralsburg, Md.. and Mrs. Ella\nBrockhurst, Ridgefield Park, N. J.,\n13 grandchildren and 13 great\ngrandchildren _\nHITCH\nMrs. Arva Elliott Hitch, 45, died\nFeb. 11 at the Beebe Hospital,\nLewes. She was the wife of Spen\ncer Hitch, at Riverdale, near Mills\nboro.\nDaughter of Mrs. Ethel Elliott\nand the late Connor R. Elliott, she\nWilliam\nalso leaves two sons.\nHitch, Georgetown, and John of\nRiverdale and one granddaughter,\nDeborah Hitch, Georgetown.\nShe was a member of the Mt.\nOlivet Church, Seaford, and was\nan employe of the Bonnie-Louise\nDress Shop in Rehoboth.\nFuneral services will ba held Sat\nurday at 2 p. m., in the Watson and\nGray Funeral Chapel, Frankford.\nThe Rev. David Mulford, rector of\nthe Episcopal Church, George\ntown, and the Rev. Frank Baynard,\npastor of the Methodist Church.\nGreenwood, will officiate. Inter\nment will be in Barratt's Chapel\nCemetery.\nFriends may call at the funeral\nchapel Friday evening from 7 to S\np. m.\nADAMS\nStephen T. Adams, 80, of Ver\nnon, near Harrington, husband of\nAnnie B. Adams, died Feb. 12 in\nthe Milford Memorial Hospital.\nA retired engineer for the Penn\nsylvania Railroad, Mr. Adams was\na former superintendent of the\nHollywood Cemetery, Harrington.\nFuneral services will be held in\nthe Berry Funeral Home, Clark\nStreet, Harrington, on Sunday at\n2 p. m. Interment will be in the\nHollywood Cemetery. The Rev.\nJohn Anderson, pastor of Prospect\nMethodist Church, near Vernon,\nwill officiate.\nFriends may call at the funeral\nhome Saturday evening.\nClassified Ads Get Results\nIN THE AIR FORCE\nt\u00e9\n77\nBy Bain\u00ab Town\u00bb*rid Dick*r\u00bbon\n2806 McAlister\nTopeka, Kansas\nFebruary 10, 1958\nDear Friends:\nWhen we moved we were given\nan eight party telephone line, and\ntickled to death to get it. Not all\nof the lines were full and until to\nday we only had (I say ONLY) five\non our line. Over the week-end\nsome one new must have moved in\nand the phone situation certainly\nhas been a Joke ever since. If my\nkitchen phone rang one long that\nwas for me, but if our extension in\nthe bedroom rang one long it would\nbe for Beth. We don't have any\nBeth in our household and the mix\nup was just nothing short of con\nfusion The telephone man just\nleft a little while ago. My exten\nsion phone had its wires crossed.\nFor a while this morning 1 thought\nmaybe mine were.\nSunday, the second, Hayes re\nturned home from his Massachus\netts trip to 8th Air Force Head\nquarters. As you know he spent a\nfew days at home and returned\nbearing gifts. One was a pewter\npitcher that I remember my par\nents using for years and years and\nyears. Pewter is all the rage now\nand I was so pleased to have this\nparticular piece. Hayes also\nbrought some lobsters fr\u00e7sh from\nthe Atlantic Ocean. How those\npoor things managed to stay \"alive\nand kicking\" in that swift, jet\nflight-back here I'll never under\nstand, but they were wiggling when\nwe dropped them in the boiling\nkettle. I make a face every time 1\nthink abo\u00f9t boiling them alive, but\nyou know if you don't you'll be the\none to suffer. They were just\nscrumptious.\nSunday afternoon a pleasant\nvoice on the other end of our tele\nphone announced that she was Mrs.\nWood, Mike Wood's mother. Mike's\nmother was asking our permission\nfor her son to take our daughter\non a roller-rink skating date. When\nI had given my permission and\nended the conversation I immed\niately turned to blushing Lynne to\nhear more. She said, \"He's nice,\nmother, hut I've already told him\nmy boy friend is in Milford.\" Mr.\nand Mrs. Wood accompanied the\ntwo eleven-year-olds and said Mike\nand Lynne had a wonderful time\ntogether. Lynne came home laugh\ning because Mike fell twice and she\ndidn't. I told Lynne that wasn't\nshowing much finesse on her part\nand she just looked at me question\nably.\nHow often do you have some pie\ndough left that you don't know\nwhat to do with? Usually I end up\ngiving it to Lynne or Dawn to play\nwith. A neighbor of mine taught\nme a neat trick this week. Into\nthe extra dough roll crumbled,\nsharp cheese. Cut into sticks about\nW by 3\". Bake them when you\nbake your pie. Of course they will\nbrown quickly. They make good\nsnacks\u2014so much so that you might\nwant to make a complete batch of\nthem.\nSaturday evening we were invit\ned by neighbors to see the Univer\nsity of Kansas basketball team play\nNebraska. The Jayhawkers (Kan\nLINCOLN\n\nMrs. Rena Morgan\nPhone: Milford 51\u00bb\u00bb\nLincoln Methodist Church\nRev. W. W. Hamilton, Pastor\nServices for Sunday, February\n16:\n11 a. m. Church School session.\nDouglas Morgan, superintendent;\nPaul White, assistant superinten\ndent. No hour in the week will\nbring as much joy and understand\ning to you than the hour spent in\nstudy of God's Holy Word each\nSunday in the class of your choice.\nA cordial invitation is extended to\nall who are not already attending\nchurch.\n4 to 4:30 p. m. \"Precious Memor\nies Broadcast\" over Georgetown\nStation, 900 on the dial.\nTickets are now on sale for the\n\"Precious Memories\" turkey supper\nwhich will be held Saturday even\ning, March 1, at the Lincoln Com\nmuni\u00e9 Hall, Inc.\n6:30 p. m. MYF under the direc\ntion of Albert Coleman, counselor,\nfor all teen-agers in and around\nLincoln. Visitors are always wel\ncome.\n7:30' p. m. Evening song and\npraise service. You will be blessed\nas you join friends in the worship\nof our Lord.\nThis week being National Boy\nScout Week, the Lincoln Troop at\ntended services in a body, along\nwith their scout master, Harry\nGlasco and assistant scout masters\nNorman Baker and Russell Brit\ntingham.\nMr. and Mrs. Glasco Dukes, Misr\nDoris Benson, Mr. and Mrs. Rob\nert Worden and son Ronnie and\nMrs. Jack Fitzgerald were received\nin Lincoln Methodist Church dur\ning iht worship service on Sundae\nmorning. Herman Benson, Archie\nCarey and William itenrett were\nelected trustees to ser T e icr a term\nof three years.\nThere will be a special meeting\nat the Lincoln Church nn Monda>\nevening, 7:30 p. m., in pj'eparatior\nfor the \"Concert\" which will bt\nheld on Sunday evening, March 16\nat 7:30 p. m. All persons having\n\"Ads\" please bring them with yoi\non Monday evening.\nThursday evening. 7 to 7:30 p\nm., sharp. Choir practice.\nThe regular monthly meeting oi\nthe Lincoln PTA will be held ir\nthe school auditorium on Thursda?\nevening, February 20, at 8 o'clock\nPlans for the coming State Conven\ntion will be discussed. The meet\ning will be in charge of Robert\nWorden, rice president. A nursery\nwill be provided for all children\nwhose parents desire to attend the\nmeeting.\nMr. and Mrs. Eugene Parker and\ndaughter Boyce spent the week-end\nin Chester, Pa., as guests of Harry\nMcClellan. On Sunday all were the\nguests of Mr. and Mrs. Robert Mc\nClellan and family of Brookhaven,\nPa\nsas) are the third team in the\ntion and we expected the\nbe pretty one sided.\nto 46, but nevertheless it\nthrilling game, too.\nWilt Chamberlain alone made\nmany points as the opposing team\nand broke a conference record,\nThis thrilled the students, but they\nalmost shook the stadium trying to\nboost their team over the one hun\ndred mark,\nThis time last year we had\nHayes' parents out here in Kansas\nwith us. Wish they could be here\nthis year to celebrate Dad Dicker\nson's birthday. It's Friday,!. Feb\nruary 14, and he is in the Milford\nMemorial Hospital. If you're in\nthe hospital visiting, wish him a\nhappy day for us, will you?\nAlways,\nElaine Townsend Dickerson\nna\ngame to\nIt was\u2014102\nwas a\nSeven foot.\n,1S\nYesterday certainly was a nice\nday for our family. All five of\nantiqued all afternoon in Law\nrence. I say \"all five\" because\nSambo persuaded us to take him\nalong. (Our Boston, Bull Dog.) We\nwere told by an antique dealer here\nin town that she believed we could\nfind two more of our Pennsylvania\nDutch plank chairs in Lawrence.\nA real friendly druggist in Law\nrence gave us a list of places to in\nvestigate and we\nll\nwere on our way.\nThe first name on our list tprned\nout to be a second hand shop and\nthe man said he had five plank\nchairs, but they turned out to be\njust old, every day, kitchen chairs.\nOur second stop impressed the\nchildren so much that afterwards\nI told them they would just have to\nerase the house from their minds\nand they both said in unison, \"But\nwe can't.\" Did you ever read about\nthe Collyer brothers who lived in\na world of wealth and filth? 1 be\nlieve they lived in New York. Well,\nthese brothers that we visited live\nin Lawrence. The floors of their\nbig home were gorgeous, all inlaid\nwoods; the curtains were surely\noriginals (never washed since the\nday they were hung\u201460 years\nago) Ivory, bisque, marble and\nbrass statues adorned each\nA thick sticky coat of dust did, tod.\nThey had so many antique chairs\nof many periods that there wasn't\nroom in this massive home to ar\nrange them, so they stacked them.\nI guess antique dealers have be\nseized these two eccentric men with\nfabulous prices for their art trea\nsures, but they continue to live in,\nunder and\"barricaded behind them.\nOur third name on our list prov\ned to be disappointing in the be\nginning, too. The middle aged\ncouple said they were recently\nstripped of their chairs by a Texas\ndealer. But then the female thought\nshe remembered seeing two chairs\nof our description in their barn.\nSure enough they were there. The\nhappy part about them is they were\nalready cleaned. These old chairs\nusually have coats and layers of\npaint. When all this is removed\nnext to the wood you'll find th\u00e9 old\nred stain. The two*chairs Hayes\nvarnished and hand rubbed last\nnight and now they are' sitting\n\"proud as peacocks\" in our dining\nroom.\nroom.\nMr. and Mrs. Russell Bradley\nand daughter Sharon of Milford\nwere dinner guests on Sunday of\nMr. and Mrs. Russell Bradley, Sr.\nMr. and Mrs. Raymond Tucker\nwere dinner guests on Saturday\nevening of Mr. and Mrs. Ralph\nTucker of Eliendale.\nMrs. Harvey Coverdale, Jr.,\ntered the Milford Memorial Hospi\ntal on Monday for observation.\nMrs. Elizabeth Satterfield enter\ntained to dinner on Sunday: Miss\nEleanor Satterfield, R. N., of Jeff\nerson Hospital, George Donovan of\nEliendale, and Mrs. Norma Marvel\nand children Virginia, Susanna and\nRose Mary of Milford.\nMr. and Mrs. Ronald Dickerson\nand three children of Rehoboth have\nrecently moved to Cedar Creek,\nformerly known as the Hubbard\nMacklin property.\nMr. and Mrs. Francis Morgan en\ntertained to a family dinner on\nSunday: Mr. and Mrs. Harvey Col\nlins, Mr. and Mrs. Elzia Collins and\nchildren of Qumboro and Mrs.\nJoshua Murray and family of Sel\nbyville.\nMrs. Emmert Shaffer and family\nof Denton, Md., spent Wednesday\nwith .her parents, Mr. and Mrs.\nHarry Truitt.\nMr. and Mrs. H. M. Burns spent\nSunday with her sister, Mrs. Hat\nte Wagamon of Milton.\nMr. and Mr$. Douglas Morgan en\ntertained to dinner on Sunday: Mr.\nand Mrs. Donald Donovan and\ndaughter Donna Mae. Ronald Rust\nof Milford and Mrs. Edith Fisher.\nMiss Hattie Harding returned\nlome on Sunday, having complet\n'd her four months nurses' train-\nng in Philadelphia General Hos\npital. Miss Harding resumed her\nluties at Milford Memorial Hos\npital on Tuesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Gerald Swain of\nNew Castle spent the week-end\nwith his parents, Mr. and Mrs. Har\n*y Swain, Sr.\nMrs. Jeanette Wordon, president\nif the Ladies Auxiliary selected the\n'ollowing members at their month\ny meeting on Monday evening to\nwork with her during the coming\n'ear: Irene Fitzgerald, assistant\n-.ecretary; Dorothy Glasco, ways\nmd means; Margaret Swain, pub\nicity. Mrs. Wordon welcomed a\nlew member to the society, Mrs.\nJnda Smith.\nCharles Rogers and his orchestra\nwill be playing this Friday evening\nit the Lincoln Community Center\n*rora 8 to 11 o'clock. Admission.\n'5c. Refreshments will be on sale.\nBobby Thomas and his orchestra\nwill be playing also at the New Lin\ncoln Community Center for the\nGeorge Washington dance to be\nheld Friday evening, February 21.\nDancing from 9 p. m. until 1 a. m.\nCabaret style. Tickets may be ob\ntained from William Warren. $3.50\nper couple. Benefit of Lincoln Com\nmunity Building.\nThere will be free skating this\nSaturday evening at the New*Lin\ncoln Community Center starting at\n7:30 o'clock. Bring your own\nskates. No steel skates allowed.\nEverybody welcome.\nen-","height":"24774","width":"19773"}}
